sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K331018
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Lumazine Synthase Microcompartment Test Construct (ECFP & EYFP with N-Terminal Arginine Tag)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: A combination of parts BBa_K331000 and BBa_K331005 for the analysis of targeting proteins within the microcompartment.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: Can independently control microcomparment formation and fluorescent protein targeting
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lisza Bruder

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K331000
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Seebeck, F. P., Woycechowsky, K. J., Zhuang, W., Rabe, J. P., and Hilvert, D., (2006). A simple tagging system for protein encapulation. J. Am. Chem. Soc. 128, 4516-4517
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This part is one that when induced by IPTG will form a microcompartment made of Lumazine Synthase. This will the arginine tails of parts BBa_K249004 and BBa_K294005 will allow for the targeting of your protein of interest into the microcompatment.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: We followed Seebeck et al. and mutated Arg83, Thr 86, Thr 120, and Gln123 to glutamates
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lisza Bruder

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K331005
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Arabinose Repressed ECFP and EYFP with N-terminal Arginine Tag
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Both the ECFP and EYFP are controlled by the same promoter which is repressed by arabinose.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lisza Bruder

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0034
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix.

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info for this part: Brian Chow
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: LacI
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: The Plac insert was PCR'd from the MG1655 strain of E.coli K12.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Inverting regulatory region controlled by LacI (BBa_C0010, BBa_C0011, etc.)

The pLac regulatory region is a 243 base-pair sequence with standard BioBrick prefix and suffix sections on its ends. It contains two protein binding sites: CAP, which is generally present in E.coli and is assocciated with cell health and availability of glucose., and LacI, the Lac inhibitor BBa_C0010 which binds in an dimerized cooperative manner to inhibit the transcription of the protein that follows. In the presence of lactose or IPTG, an analog of lactose, LacI is unable to correctly bind and inhibit transcription. This allows BBa_R0010 to be used as a inverter or as a detector of lactose or IPTG.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: LacI binds to this regulator. This part is incompatible with species containing active LacI coding regions. Lactose and IPTG disable the operation of LacI and this regulator. This part is incompatible with environments containing lactose or lactose analogs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0010
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcriptional terminator consisting of a 64 bp stem-loop.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Randy Rettberg

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0030
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Strong RBS based on Ron Weiss thesis. Strength is considered relative to <bb_part>BBa_B0031</bb_part>, <bb_part>BBa_B0032</bb_part>, <bb_part>BBa_B0033</bb_part>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Varies from -6 to +1 region from original sequence to accomodate BioBricks suffix ("orig" in figure 4-14 of Ron Weiss thesis).

No secondary structures are formed in the given RBS region. Users should check for secondary structures induced in the RBS by upstream and downstream elements in the +50 to -50 region, as such structures will greatly affect the strength of the RBS. Contact info Brian Chow
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr IAP, 2003.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K249002
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Lumazine Synthase is an enzyme which creates Lumazine, a product which aggregates forming a hollow spheroid which can act as a mirocompartment, or artificial organelle. The Lumazine forms negatively charged pores, which can be used to introduce proteins. The proteins which are being introduced into the microcompartment must be equipped with an Arginine Tag.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: point mutations of EcoRI and PstI sites?
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Roxanne Shank

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K249008
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: BioBrick YFP with synthesized N-termianl Arg Tag
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This Yellow Fluorescent protein has been fused with 10 N-terminal Arginines to target it into the Lumazine-based microcompartment. Has a double terminator at the end
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Roxanne Shank

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_K331001
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance:
The idea came from:
Seebeck, F. P., Woycechowsky, K. J., Zhuang, W., Rabe, J. P., and Hilvert, D., (2006). A simple tagging system for protein encapulation. J. Am. Chem. Soc. 128, 4516-4517
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This protein is the ECFP fused with the N-terminal Arginine tag found in BBa_K240994. It is designed to be part of a construct for targeting into the lumazine synthase microcompatment (BBa_K331000)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Lisza Bruder

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I13453
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: PBad promoter from I0500 without AraC.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: jkm

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: p(tetR)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Lutz, R., Bujard, H., Nucleic Acids Research (1997) 25, 1203-1210.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Sequence for pTet inverting regulator driven by the TetR protein.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: BBa_R0040 TetR-Regulated Promoter is based on a cI promoter. It has been modified to include two TetR binding sites and the BioBrick standard assembly head and tail restriction sites.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: June Rhee, Connie Tao, Ty Thomson, Louis Waldman

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: tetR
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Elowitz, M. B. Transport, Assembly, and Dynamics in Systems of Interacting Proteins. Thesis, Princeton Univ., Princeton (1999)
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Coding region for the TetR protein without the Ribosome Binding Site. Modified with an LVA tail for rapid degradation of the protein and faster fall time for the emission. TetR binds to the pTet regulator (BBa_R0040). aTc (anhydrotetracycline) binds to TetR and inhibits its operation.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
References (unparsed) here:

Elowitz, M. B. Transport, Assembly, and Dynamics in Systems of Interacting Proteins. Thesis, Princeton Univ., Princeton (1999).

Lutz R, Bujard H., Independent and tight regulation of transcriptional units in Escherichia coli via the LacR/O, the TetR/O and AraC/I1-I2 regulatory elements. Nucleic Acids Res. 1997 Mar 15;25(6):1203-10. PMID: 9092630

References (unparsed) here:

Elowitz, M. B. Transport, Assembly, and Dynamics in Systems of Interacting Proteins. Thesis, Princeton Univ., Princeton (1999).

Lutz R, Bujard H., Independent and tight regulation of transcriptional units in Escherichia coli via the LacR/O, the TetR/O and AraC/I1-I2 regulatory elements. Nucleic Acids Res. 1997 Mar 15;25(6):1203-10. PMID: 9092630

BBa_C0040 TetR Protein is based on the TetR sequence from Elowitz's repressilator. It has been modified to include a rapid degradation LVA tail, and includes the BioBrick standard assembly head and tail restriction sites. The RBS has been removed. The stop codon has been changed from TAA to a double stop codon TAATAA.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: June Rhee, Connie Tao, Ty Thomson, Louis Waldman.
